review_blob: I should have know better: A belgian lager in a champagne bottle. Clear yellow with white shortlived head with good lacing. Metallic blood-like, aroma of stale hops going tino a bland flavor with watery aftertaste. Probably the worst lager in South Africa.

Bottle. Light brown with tan stable head. Aroma is nutty and a bit fruity with notes of chocolate. Flavor is very smooth and mouth feel is surprisingly big for a small beer like this - would be even better with less  carbonation. Short aftertaste and a little watery finish. Amazing effort for a beer of only 3,5% and probably the best bottled mild ale I have had.

Can and bottle. Clear straw colored body with white fluffy head. Flavor is malty and bittersweet with sugary notes. One of the better lagers around, and by far the best from any of the larger  breweries in SA. although it becomes cloying in the long run.

Can and bottle on several occasions. A gem in a trash can of pale flavorless lager. Black with faint red hues and firm, but bigbubbled white head. Sweet roasty flavor with hints of bitter coffee and licorice. Mouthfeel is viscous but unfortunate a bit too high in carbonation. Amazing that a brewery like Castle can actually make something as enjoyable as this.

Bottle. Dark brown with read hues with a tan head. Aroma of chocolate, socks and burned toast. Flavos is thin, like creamted toast dissolved in water. Body is watery thin. An astringent mess and is not recommended. try Castle Stout instead.

Bottle from the brewery. Brown to reddish beer with small white head. Caramel, earthy hops, toffee in aroma leading to a thin and pretty bitter taste. Some roasted notes sneeks in also. Quite bitter to SA standards and really drinkable. It lacks somewhat in MF department and it seems like it would be a lot better without the heavy filtration. But all in all a nice beer in a country with very few hoppy beers.
